        </blockquote>
        
        <h3>Grant Types and Facts</h3>
        <p>
          Most Grants are given out by the government and nongovernmental organizations to nonprofits and educational institutions whose focus is medicine, education, scientific research or technology development. Only few certified lenders and business bankers give grants, they are often are interested in giving money to specific groups and types of organizations, such as educational institutions. In most cases, your business must be devoted to new technology research or be a nonprofit in order to apply for most grants. 
        </p>

        <h3>Minority and Women Owned Grants</h3>
        <p>
          There are many nongovernment grants issued to small business owners based on ethnic minorities, women, and other underrepresented people in business. Business owners must meet the specifications of the grant, and the business or nonprofit organization should meet whatever criteria the organization may have.  For instance, if you apply for a nongovernmental grant that provides grants to women-owned businesses, at least one woman must own the business.
        </p>

        <h3>Small Business Innovation Research Program (SBIR)</h3>
        <p>
          One great resource for grants is the Small Business Innovation Research Program (SBIR). SBIR is a competitive program that encourages small business owners to explore technological potential and provides the incentive to profit from commercialization. This program is intended to help small business owners contribute to the R&D development within the United States and has been the seed funding for many, now large corporations.

          <h3>SBIR Qualifications:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>American-owned and independently operated</li>
            <li>For-profit small business</li>
            <li>Principal researcher employed by business</li>
            <li>Fewer than 500 employees</li>
          </ul>
        </p>
